ge build args might lead to an \\\"Unknown module: java.base\\\" error. It doesn't seem like a problem for a public top-level object since it isn't a test class. I also need to consider if `Dns(system).manager.path.name` might not return IO-DNS if it's asynchronous. \\n\\nI should explore how `Dns(system).manager` could behave during actor construction, especially with potential asynchronous creation. I’m thinking if I can use `Await.result()` to force resolution and ensure everything finishes correctly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing actor test failures**\\n\\nI'm realizing that if an actor fails, it might not always lead to a test failure, showing up only in the logs. Is that acceptable? I think tests should really exercise all capabilities. For the agent JVM, I believe line 242 will succeed with the manager being alive. It seems logical to assert that it's alive, but I’m wondering if I should ensure that such failures surface clearly in the tests. I want to balance thorough testing with practical failures.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented focused coverage for `org.apache.pekko.io.dns.DnsSettings$`.\n\nChanges:\n- Added dedicated Scala test file:\n  - `tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/src/test/scala/org_apache_pekko/pekko_actor_2_13/DnsSettingsTest.scala`\n- The test forces Pekko DNS default nameserver discovery to skip the JNDI path and exercise the `sun.net.dns.ResolverConfiguration` reflection fallback.\n- Updated:\n  - `tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/build.gradle`\n- Added `--add-opens=java.base/sun.net.dns=ALL-UNNAMED` for JVM tests and native-image builds so the fallback can invoke the JDK resolver methods and reach all active call sites.\n\nI did not run compilation or tests, per instructions.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_010a55ec37af26c80169fb219a818c8193af2f996e746accc3\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usa